Byron describes the deaths of the Assyrian soldiers with calm language. For
example, he says “the eyes of the sleepers wax’d deadly and chill, / And their
hearts but once heaved, and for ever grew still!”.
In ‘The Destruction of Sennacherib’, Byron presents the soldiers’ deaths as being
eerily calm by describing how their hearts heaved “once” and then “grew still”.
